title: For Sale/Trade:  GSG 1911 22 lr w/ ammo
postcontent:
German Sporting Goods (GSG), a division of American Tactical Imports (ATI), has created a full size 1911 frame that fires 22 lr. This is NOT a conversion kit; this gun was made for plinking. 

I purchased the gun new, and have put ~250 rounds through it with only 5 FTL early on in the process. The gun has been meticulously cleaned and maintained, and is sighted in perfectly.

When first purchasing the gun, I saw reviews complaining about running errors, and that, gun to gun, it is hit or miss if it will run right. Well this one hits it out of the park. The gun has only ever seen federal bulk ammo, and has run very well, as described above. Most reviews also give the GSG 1911-22 high marks all around.

Don't waste time buying a new gun at new gun prices with the chance that it will not work anyways. Most places are selling the gun around $375, but that only comes with 1 mag (which are expensive on their own at $35-40) and no ammo. This package has it all!

As shown in the pictures, the gun shows no wear outside of normal running marks, and has never been holster worn. The gun comes with an extra magazine, original hard case, gun lock (w/ keys), fake suppressor can, extra set of sights and buffer ring, take down tools, and instruction booklet and materials. Also included are 100 rounds of 22 lr ammo.

Will only make a FTF deal, and buyer must have Indiana DL and LTCH.

Caliber: .22LR Sporting Chamber
Barrel: 16" M4 Profile Barrel, WASP Treated 4140 Chrome-Moly Steel, 1:16" Twist
Hand Guard: M4 Hand Guard
Gas Block: Low Profile Railed Gas Block
Bolt Group: Phosphated .22 Bolt Group
NO sights / NO mag 

W.A.S.P. Treated Barrel
(Weapon Armament Surface Protection) is a salt bath ferritic nitrocarburizing surface conversion process or more commonly referred to as nitriding. The nitriding conversion is applied to the barrel inside and out, along with the front sight base on our LE rifles and uppers. Nitriding offers improved wear, abrasion, and corrosion resistance when compared to hard chrome lining or phosphating.

Unlike chrome lining, where the chrome is built up on the surface, nitriding converts the surface without the risk of dimensional build up. CMMG Pioneered the use of this nitriding process on AR barrels and has been using it for many years.
